dynamicalSystems
Class Relationship

java.lang.Object
  dynamicalSystems.Entity
      dynamicalSystems.Relationship

public class Relationship
extends Entity

This class manages how the system entities, are interrelated. For example : There are two entities 'a' and 'b' connected by a operator '+'. this indicates that to calculate the result of that relationship, will be done, a + b ( or b + a ).It depends on the precedence. The first parameter, is the first entity to be considered. May be a relationship among elements, or between one element and other relationship, or even a relationship among relationships. On this last case, the relations more internals, are considered firstly.

Author:
Wellington Bruno

Field Detail

ifThenElse

protected IfThenElse ifThenElse
When the relationship equation is an if_then_else equation,this attribute must be adjusted. you shall do it, for doing something like : element.setIfThenElse(new IfThenElse(Condition,result1,result2)); and after it, doing element.connect(Relationship.IF_THEN_ELSE);

WITH_LOOKUPS

public static final char WITH_LOOKUPS
Constant that indicates that the relationship is a LookUp. When the relationship is a lookUp, the out value,is find for a given table.

Constructs a relationship with the multipliers different than default For example,to do something like

(2 *object1) + (3 * object2)

you shall do new Relationship (2,object1,'+',3,object2);

Parameters:
f1 - The multiplier for object1 value
ob1 - The first entity of relationship
relation - The way how the entities are interrelated. The user may use the constants available on this class, or enter a valid char that indicates what to do with the Entities.
f2 - The multiplier for object2 value
ob2 - The second entity of relationship
